<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-samplesandclt" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Sampling distributions and the central limit theorem</title>
    <p>
        The law of large numbers provides an important theoretical result: as the sample size increases, 
        sample statistics such as the sample mean tend to approach the corresponding population parameters. 
        However, this result describes what happens as the sample size becomes very large and does not tell us how sample statistics 
        behave for the finite samples encountered in practice.
    </p>
    <p>
        In most real-world studies, researchers work with limited sample sizes. Consequently, 
        sample statistics vary from one sample to another because of random sampling variation. 
        To understand and quantify this variability, statisticians study the <em>sampling distribution</em> of a statistic. 
        Sampling distributions provide the foundation for measuring the accuracy of estimates, constructing confidence intervals, 
        and performing hypothesis tests.
    </p>
    <p>
        One of the most important results in statistical inference is the <em>Central Limit Theorem</em>. 
        This theorem describes the behaviour of the sampling distribution of the sample mean and explains why the normal distribution plays such a central role in statistical methods. 
        The following sections introduce sampling distributions before presenting the Central Limit Theorem.
    </p>

    <xi:include href="subsections/samplesandclt/subsec-samplingdists.ptx" />
